al literature by offering new insights into the heterogeneous ways in which African men are performing, negotiating and experiencing masculinity.Through their analysis of the depictions in film and literature of masculinities in colonial, independent and post-independent Africa, the contributors open some key African texts to a more obviously politicized set of meanings. Collectively, the essays provide space for rethinking current theory on gender and masculinity: - how only some of the most popular theories in masculinity studies in the West hold true in African contexts; - howWestern masculinities react with indigenous masculinities on the continent; - how masculinity and femininity in Africa seem to reside more on a continuum of cultural practices than on absolutely opposite planes; - andhow generation often functions as a more potent metaphor than gender. Lahoucine Ouzgane is Associate Professor of English & Film Studies, University of Alberta, Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aMasculinity in literature. 0aMasculinity in motion pictures. 0aMen in literature. 0aMen in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszAfricaxHistory. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAlden, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanco, Lindsey Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBanco, Linsey Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryce, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEpprecht, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammond, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/